I have always been a history nut and in my late teens I spent a year studying Polish history of the 19th century. Much of it was the history of Polish Jews. The Yiddish newspaper "Warszojer Jidisze Cajtung" is an important historical source for the period. I was learning German at the time, and I was amazed to discover how much of the articles I actually understood: it seemed like a blend of German and Polish (there obviously must have been some Hebrew, too, but I did not know much about it back then), generally spelled as German would be if you wrote it down as it sounds in Polish. Sadly, the entry on it in Wikipedia is in Polish only: <a href="https://pl.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warszojer_Jidisze_Cajtung" target="_blank">https://pl.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warszojer_Jidisze_Cajtung</a> (there is a very short version in German, too). I'll paste a DeepL translation of the entry in a further reply.

